# Prisma Patterns

## Usage rules
- Inject `PrismaService` via constructor DI — never import `PrismaClient` directly in services
- Use `PrismaService` which extends `PrismaClient` and handles connect/disconnect lifecycle
- All DB calls must be `await`ed — no fire-and-forget DB writes

## Schema conventions
- All models have `id String @id @default(cuid())` — no auto-increment integers
- All models have `createdAt DateTime @default(now())`
- Add `@@index` for fields used in `where` or `orderBy` clauses
- Use `Json?` for flexible metadata — never store JSON as a string
- Use `String` for enum-like fields (scenario type, status) — simpler than Prisma enums for this domain

## Forbidden
- `$queryRaw` / `$executeRaw` — use Prisma client API only
- Multiple `PrismaClient` instances — use the singleton `PrismaService`
- Storing passwords/tokens in the database as plaintext
- Omitting `migrate deploy` in production startup

## After schema changes
Run in order:
```bash
npx prisma migrate dev --name <description>   # creates migration
npx prisma generate                            # regenerates client
```
Restart the backend container after migration.

## Example service pattern
```typescript
@Injectable()
export class FooService {
  constructor(private readonly prisma: PrismaService) {}

  async findById(id: string): Promise<Foo> {
    return this.prisma.foo.findUniqueOrThrow({ where: { id } });
  }
}
```
